## Procedure

### Step 0: Locate plan root + project slug

```bash
PLAN_ROOT="${CLAUDE_PLANS_DIR:-$HOME/.gstack/projects/$(basename "$PWD")}/avatars"
mkdir -p "$PLAN_ROOT"
echo "PLAN_ROOT: $PLAN_ROOT"
```

Ask the user for a project slug (e.g., `tsl-tutor`, `support-bot`, `cinematic-narrator`).
Final outputs land at `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/`.

### Step 1: Confirm intent + scope

AskUserQuestion (preamble format):
- **Re-ground:** current project + branch.
- **Simplify:** "Avatar architecture is five interlocking decisions (face, body, voice,
  animation, expression) that lock 80% of the user-perceived quality. Picking wrong
  on any one of them looks uncanny no matter how good the others are. Let's lock the
  use case before we touch subsystems."
- **RECOMMENDATION:** A because subsystem-by-subsystem design without a use-case anchor
  is how teams ship mismatched stacks (cinematic face on a real-time pipeline = stutter).
- **Options:**
  - A) Design a full new avatar stack from scratch. Completeness: 10/10.
  - B) I already have subsystems picked — just give me the integration plan. Completeness:
    7/10 (this skill is overkill; consider per-subsystem skills directly).
  - C) Evaluating two architectures head-to-head. Completeness: 9/10 (this skill will
    produce two parallel plans for `/voice-eval` + humanness eval to compare).

### Step 2: Gather the spec (interactive or `--spec`)

For each input row in the table above, AskUserQuestion with:
- **Simplify:** plain-language gloss of why the field matters.
- **RECOMMENDATION:** sensible default with rationale.
- **Options:** 2-4 concrete choices each, with a Completeness score.

For `use case` specifically gloss as: "real-time conversational means the user can
interrupt and the avatar has to respond inside ~1 second end-to-end. Cinematic means
you can spend minutes per second of footage. Sign performer means hand articulation
is non-negotiable. Scripted explainer is the easiest — pre-render everything."

For `target latency` gloss: "end-to-end latency is from user-speech-end to
avatar-mouth-open. Streaming (<400ms) requires a real-time lip-sync model
(MuseTalk / audio2lip) and rules out diffusion-based face models. Anything above
~1500ms feels like a video call on bad wifi."

For `expressivity scope` gloss: "neutral means the face does mouth movement and
nothing else — fine for a navigation prompt, lethal for a teaching tutor. Emotional
range adds Ekman-style discrete emotions. Full conversational beats adds turn-taking
cues, back-channels, micro-expressions — that's what makes the avatar feel like it's
listening."

### Step 3: Architecture recommendation

Apply the decision matrices below, then write `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/ARCHITECTURE.md`.

**Face model matrix:**

| If user needs... | Recommended face model | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| Photoreal cinematic, no real-time constraint | **3D Gaussian Splatting** (GaussianAvatars, GaussianHead) | Best photoreal quality 2024; ~30fps render on consumer GPU once trained |
| Real-time portrait talking head from one photo | **2D portrait + MuseTalk** | <100ms inference; works zero-shot from a single frame |
| Multi-view consistency required (turning head, walking) | **NeRF-based avatar** (NerFACE, INSTA) or **Gaussian Splatting** | NeRF has slower render but cleaner geometry; GS faster but needs more capture |
| Riggable, animatable from blendshapes | **3DMM / FLAME / MetaHuman** | Industry-standard parametric face; works with FACS action units cleanly |
| Sign-performer (face matters for non-manual features) | **FLAME-based mesh + facial blendshapes** | Required: brow raise / eye gaze / mouth shapes drive ASL/TSL grammar |
| Edge / mobile / browser | **2D portrait + lightweight lip-sync** (Wav2Lip distilled / SadTalker quantized) | Only viable face model at <500MB and CPU/NPU inference |
| Stylized / cartoon | **2D rigged sprite** + Live2D / Spine | Photoreal models look broken when stylized; rigged 2D is the right tool |

**Body model matrix:**

| If user needs... | Recommended body model | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| Head-and-shoulders only | None — face model alone | Don't over-engineer |
| Half-body, gesture-light | **SMPL-X (face + hands + body)** rendered as upper-body crop | Standard parametric body; integrates with gesture synth |
| Full body, presenter-style | **SMPL-X** + retargeted gestures | Industry standard; gesture-synth models target SMPL-X joints |
| Full body w/ fine hand articulation (sign / craft) | **SMPL-X w/ MANO hands** | MANO is the de facto hand model; required for sign-performing avatars |
| VR / metaverse avatar | **VRM (VRoid) format** | Open standard; works with Unity / VRChat / Pretext pipelines |
| 2D-stylized | **Rigged 2D body** (Spine / DragonBones) | Pairs with 2D face model |

**Animation driver matrix:**

| Use case | Lip-sync driver | Gesture driver | Expression driver |
|---|---|---|---|
| Real-time conversational | `/lip-sync` w/ MuseTalk | `/gesture-synth` w/ light beat-only model | `/expression-synth` w/ conversational-beat surface |
| Cinematic | `/lip-sync` w/ EMO or latentSync | `/gesture-synth` w/ GENEA-SOTA / retargeted MoCap | `/expression-synth` w/ full FACS surface |
| Sign performer | `/avatar-sign` (drives mouth, brows, gaze from gloss) | `/avatar-sign` (drives hands + body) | `/avatar-sign` (drives non-manual features) |
| Scripted explainer | `/lip-sync` w/ SadTalker or EMO | Pre-keyframed or `/gesture-synth` offline | Pre-keyframed or `/expression-synth` offline |

For each recommendation include in ARCHITECTURE.md:
- The picked face / body / voice / animation triple, with version pins.
- Framework / engine: PyTorch for ML subsystems; Three.js / Babylon / Unity / Unreal
  for rendering layer; ONNX Runtime for edge deployment.
- Hardware envelope per subsystem (training and inference, broken out).
- The integration topology: which subsystem owns the master clock (usually audio),
  how A/V sync is enforced, where state lives between turns.
- What this stack CAN'T do — explicit limitations so the user doesn't get burned.

### Step 4: Subsystems doc

Write `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/SUBSYSTEMS.md` covering each subsystem with:
- Picked model + version pin.
- Inputs / outputs / data format (e.g., "MuseTalk consumes 25fps RGB + 16kHz audio,
  emits RGB").
- Training data needs (or "uses public checkpoint, no training").
- Inference cost (GPU memory, latency per chunk, throughput).
- Hand-off skill (e.g., "the face model is handed to `/lip-sync` Step 3").

### Step 5: Integration doc

Write `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/INTEGRATION.md` covering:
- **Master clock:** which subsystem drives time (audio for streaming, video timeline
  for cinematic).
- **A/V sync mechanism:** explicit sync points (e.g., "viseme timestamps from
  `/lip-sync` are emitted at 25Hz, gesture timestamps at 30Hz, expression at 60Hz —
  the renderer interpolates").
- **State management:** conversational state (turn-taking, back-channels) lives in
  `/expression-synth`'s beat-cue surface; emotion state hands across subsystems via
  shared valence-arousal scalars.
- **Failure modes:** what happens when lip-sync misses a frame, when gesture model
  stalls, when TTS streams a chunk late. Per-subsystem degradation policy.
- **Telemetry:** what each subsystem emits (latency p50/p99, sync drift, etc.) for
  the eval harness.

### Step 6: Eval-humanness doc

Write `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/EVAL-HUMANNESS.md` calling into the eval harness with the
metric set this stack needs:

- **Perceived humanness (MOS-style human panel)** — required for any production tier.
- **Lip-sync quality** (Sync-D, LSE-C from `/lip-sync` EVAL.md, cross-ref Family L
  `/voice-eval` for cross-modal sync).
- **Gesture appropriateness** (FGD from `/gesture-synth` EVAL.md).
- **Expression naturalness** (from `/expression-synth` EVAL.md).
- **Sign-fluency** if `/avatar-sign` is in the stack — native-deaf-reviewer loop is
  mandatory; no MOS-equivalent automated metric is trustworthy enough yet.
- **Uncanny-valley early-warning probe** — show a 5-second clip to N reviewers, ask
  "does this person feel alive?" — gate threshold per quality tier.

Eval cadence: per-subsystem during build; end-to-end nightly during integration;
full human panel before release.

### Step 7: Hand-off

Print the four file paths. AskUserQuestion:
- **Simplify:** "Architecture is on disk. Next step is to design each subsystem in
  parallel — `/lip-sync`, `/gesture-synth`, `/expression-synth`, optionally
  `/avatar-sign`. Or run `/autoplan-full` to expand the whole stack into a build pipeline."
- **RECOMMENDATION:** B — run subsystem skills in dependency order so each plan
  references this architecture.
- **Options:**
  - A) Run /autoplan-full on the architecture. Completeness: 10/10.
  - B) Walk through subsystem skills now (`/lip-sync`, then `/gesture-synth`, then
    `/expression-synth`, optionally `/avatar-sign`). Completeness: 10/10.
  - C) Stop — I'll review the docs first. Completeness: 9/10.

